def video_frame_map(info: VideoInfo, buffer: Gst.Buffer, flags: Gst.MapFlags | int) -> tuple[bool, VideoFrame]:
    """
    Use ``info`` and ``buffer`` to fill in the values of ``frame``. ``frame`` is usually
    allocated on the stack, and you will pass the address to the :class:`GstVideo.VideoFrame`
    structure allocated on the stack; :func:`GstVideo.video_frame_map` will then fill in
    the structures with the various video-specific information you need to access
    the pixels of the video buffer. You can then use accessor macros such as
    GST_VIDEO_FRAME_COMP_DATA(), GST_VIDEO_FRAME_PLANE_DATA(),
    GST_VIDEO_FRAME_COMP_STRIDE(), GST_VIDEO_FRAME_PLANE_STRIDE() etc.
    to get to the pixels.

    |[<!-- language="C" -->
      :class:`GstVideo.VideoFrame` vframe;
      ...
      // set RGB pixels to black one at a time
      if (:func:`GstVideo.video_frame_map` (&vframe, video_info, video_buffer, GST_MAP_WRITE)) {
        guint8 *pixels = GST_VIDEO_FRAME_PLANE_DATA (vframe, 0);
        guint stride = GST_VIDEO_FRAME_PLANE_STRIDE (vframe, 0);
        guint pixel_stride = GST_VIDEO_FRAME_COMP_PSTRIDE (vframe, 0);

        for (h = 0; h < height; ++h) {
          for (w = 0; w < width; ++w) {
            guint8 *pixel = pixels + h * stride + w * pixel_stride;

            memset (pixel, 0, pixel_stride);
          }
        }

        :meth:`GstVideo.VideoFrame.unmap` (&vframe);
      }
      ...
    ]|

    All video planes of ``buffer`` will be mapped and the pointers will be set in
    ``frame``->data.

    The purpose of this function is to make it easy for you to get to the video
    pixels in a generic way, without you having to worry too much about details
    such as whether the video data is allocated in one contiguous memory chunk
    or multiple memory chunks (e.g. one for each plane); or if custom strides
    and custom plane offsets are used or not (as signalled by :class:`GstVideo.VideoMeta` on
    each buffer). This function will just fill the :class:`GstVideo.VideoFrame` structure
    with the right values and if you use the accessor macros everything will
    just work and you can access the data easily. It also maps the underlying
    memory chunks for you.
    """
def video_frame_map_id(info: VideoInfo, buffer: Gst.Buffer, id: int, flags: Gst.MapFlags | int) -> tuple[bool, VideoFrame]:
    """
    Use ``info`` and ``buffer`` to fill in the values of ``frame`` with the video frame
    information of frame ``id``.

    When ``id`` is -1, the default frame is mapped. When ``id`` != -1, this function
    will return ``False`` when there is no :class:`GstVideo.VideoMeta` with that id.

    All video planes of ``buffer`` will be mapped and the pointers will be set in
    ``frame``->data.
    """
